detailed_description.textblock:
This is a 2-phase study where Phase 1 deploys a quasi-experimental design (N=35 family caregivers) and Phase 2 has a delayed-intervention randomized clinical trial (N=266). Both Phases involve the delivery of an evidence-based, tele-coaching intervention, Care-Resistant Behavior Internet Training (CuRB-IT).
The purposes of this two-phase study are:
1. to examine the feasibility of delivering the CuRB-IT intervention [Phase 1];
2. examine the efficacy of CuRB-IT in increasing the self-efficacy of family caregivers of persons living with dementia to handle care-resistant behaviors (CRB) [Phases 1&2];
3. further test the efficacy of CuRB-IT in improving caregivers coping strategies (a) among the experimental (immediate-intervention group) as compared to the control (delayed-intervention group) (between groups) and (b) within-person from pre- to post- intervention [Phase 2];
4. examine intervention decay at 3- and 6-months post intervention to determine performance of intervention and inform scheduling of booster sessions [Phase 2];
5. assess the efficacy of the CuRB-IT intervention in preventing onset of poor coping strategies by family caregivers [Phases 1&2];
6. evaluate [Phase 1] and test [Phase 2] the hypothesized mechanism of action that increased CRB self-efficacy and use of CuRB-IT problem-focused coping strategies mediate the relationship between CRB stress appraisal and caregiving activities.
